Jenkins Setup on Ubuntu (Practical Commands)

1️⃣ Switch to root user
Allows running administrative commands without typing sudo each time.

sudo -i

2️⃣ Update package list
Refreshes the system package index to get the latest available packages.

apt-get update

3️⃣ Check if Java is installed
Jenkins requires Java to run. This command verifies whether Java is already present.

java

4️⃣ Install OpenJDK 17
Installs Java (required dependency for Jenkins).

sudo apt update && sudo apt install -y openjdk-17-jdk

5️⃣ Add Jenkins repository key
Adds the official Jenkins GPG key to verify package authenticity.

sudo wget -O /etc/apt/keyrings/jenkins-keyring.asc \
https://pkg.jenkins.io/debian-stable/jenkins.io-2026.key

6️⃣ Add Jenkins repository to the system
Registers the Jenkins package source so Ubuntu can download Jenkins.

echo "deb [signed-by=/etc/apt/keyrings/jenkins-keyring.asc]" \
https://pkg.jenkins.io/debian-stable binary/ | sudo tee \
/etc/apt/sources.list.d/jenkins.list > /dev/null

7️⃣ Update package list again
Loads the newly added Jenkins repository packages.

sudo apt update

8️⃣ Install Jenkins
Downloads and installs Jenkins on the system.

sudo apt install jenkins

9️⃣ Verify Jenkins service status
Checks whether Jenkins is running successfully.

systemctl status jenkins
